as a global cultural phenomenon of the Early Modern period, its reverberations reaching as far as Viceregal Peru. The tradition of the pastoral as a site for the discussion of 'great matters in theforest' has deep roots, and re-emerges to praise the urban hearts of empire. Furthermore, it proves to be a site of spiritual encounter--a poetic space that frames the staging of indigenous conversion in the poetry of Diego Mexiaand Fernando de Valverde. Within the intricacies of this literary construct, surface artistry sustains an effect of artless innocence that is vibrantly contested across the secular, sacred, parodic and colonial text.Anne Holloway is a Lecturer in Spanish, Queen's University Belfast.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPastoral poetry, SpanishxHistory and criticism. 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aArcadia.  aBurlesque.  aColonial text.  aDiego Mexia.  aEarly Modern period.  aHispanic studies.  aLiterary criticism.  aLuisa de Carvajal y Mendoza.  aPastoral.  aPedro Soto de Rojas.  aPoetry.  aRenaissance literature.  aSacred text.  aSatire.  aSpanich Baroque.  aSpanish poetry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782049555?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782049555423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782049555/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles